      "goal": "A1 *->* A2: N3",
      "status": "attack found",
      "confidence": 78,
      "justification": "N3 is only ever sent inside {N3,A1}pk(A2), so confidentiality against outsiders holds, but the goal is a secure-channel style claim (confidential + authenticated). A2 has no cryptographic evidence that the sender is A1: the ciphertext is not signed/MACed and public-key encryption alone does not authenticate the origin. An attacker can start a run with A2 by sending {N3,I}pk(A2) for attacker-chosen N3, making A2 accept N3 as if it came from A1. Thus the authenticated aspect of the secure-channel goal fails.",
      "two_session_trace": "Session 1: I -> A2: {N3,I}pk(A2) (I chooses N3). A2 proceeds believing peer is A1 and accepts N3.\nSession 2: A1 -> A2: {N3',A1}pk(A2) (honest run, unrelated)."
    },
    {
      "goal_id": 2,
      "goal": "A2 *->* A1: N4",
      "status": "attack found",
      "confidence": 74,
      "justification": "N4 is sent as {N3,N4,A2}pk(A1), which keeps N4 confidential from outsiders, but does not authenticate that it was created by A2. Since A1 cannot verify the origin of an encryption under pk(A1), an attacker can fabricate {N3,N4,I}pk(A1) and induce A1 to accept an attacker-chosen N4 as if it came from A2 (or at least without assurance it did). Therefore the authenticated/secure-channel claim for N4 fails even though secrecy of N4 against passive eavesdroppers would hold.",
      "two_session_trace": "Session 1: A1 -> I: {N3,A1}pk(A2) (I intercepts; N3 remains unknown to I). I -> A1: {N3_fake,N4,I}pk(A1) (I chooses N3_fake,N4). A1 accepts N4 without authenticating A2.\nSession 2: A2 -> A1: {N3',N4',A2}pk(A1) (honest run, unrelated)."
    }
  ]
